<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / Names spurred on by Gooda judgment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Action groups of Lloyd's Names held up in the legislative queue to claim
damages yesterday seized on Tuesday's Gooda Walker judgment to urge the
professional agencies they are suing to agree out-of-court settlements.
The success of the Gooda Walker action group in the High Court in winning
compensation for negligent underwriting during the late 1980s has led others
to believe their hand has been strengthened.
But the Gooda Walker case has also highlighted the limited pool of errors
and omissions (E&amp;O) insurance cover held by members' agencies being sued.
Claims for negligence would be paid by this cover. Lloyd's Names earlier
this year rejected the insurance market's settlement worth Pounds 900m.
Lawyers for E&amp;O insurers yesterday refused to discuss publicly the
possibility of settlements. But Mr Alan Porter, chairman of the Devonshire
Names Action Group, which is claiming Pounds 174m on behalf of 1,140
members, said the Gooda Walker verdict provided a basis for a possible
settlement for other 'spiral' cases, where underwriters agreed to cover
others against excessive losses from catastrophes. The next 'spiral' case,
mounted by Names on the Feltrim syndicates, starts later this month.
Mr Josceline Grove, secretary of the Secretan Names Association, urged
Lloyd's, which so far has said only that it would facilitate a deal, to take
a stronger lead in forging a settlement.
</TEXT>
