FT  06 OCT 94 / Adams says meetings with US officials going well
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, said that his meetings with US
officials in Washington this week had brought 'an enormous move forward for
peace and for justice and reconciliation in Ireland', George Graham and
David Owen write.
He added: 'We have made the hope more of a reality today.'
Mr Adams's comments came after he had met senior officials at the US State
Department on Tuesday in the first official contact between the US
administration and Sinn Fein, and after a lengthy debate with Mr Ken
Maginnis, the Ulster Unionist MP, on the CNN cable television network.
But the debate, touted as the highlight of Mr Adams's two-week tour of the
US, was rated as a 'no-score draw' by observers. The two men tried to outdo
each other with stories of how many times they had been shot at or bombed.
Mr Adams (pictured right) sought repeatedly to put Mr Maginnis (left) on the
spot by offering a handshake. Mr Maginnis refused and spoke only to the
show's host, Larry King, rather than to Mr Adams.
But both men came under attack from viewers - all of them claiming to be
Irish - for refusing to do what was necessary to bring about peace.
Mr Maginnis's decision to participate in a debate with Mr Adams was attacked
by Mr Peter Robinson, deputy leader of the hardline Democratic Unionist
party. He said the arguments in favour of taking part were 'heavily
outweighed by the principles that have been given away by him sitting down
on the same platform as the leader of the Provisional movement'.
