<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / Legal challenge to Tube strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The RMT transport union faces a legal challenge to stop the 24-hour Tube
strike which is due to start at 7.30 this evening.
London Underground is questioning the validity of the union's ballot which
resulted in support for industrial action. It said last night: 'We are
considering seeking a High Court injunction to prevent the disruption. There
were irregularities in the ballot.'
The RMT is demanding a basic pay rise of at least 4 per cent although the
rest of the staff employed by London Underground have agreed to a pay
settlement this year of 2.5 per cent.
A total of 15 hours of talks at the conciliation service Acas earlier this
week failed to produce a deal. London Underground said it was willing to
hold further discussions but emphasised it would not improve its 2.5 per
cent offer.
The company says that a number of its employees who are RMT members failed
to receive voting papers for the ballot, although they were entitled to
participate.
The union denied this yesterday, pointing out that London Underground had
given no indication of how many employees were covered by the complaint. It
said that its solicitors were considering the position.
Only 37 per cent of the 7,500 RMT members at London Underground took part in
the ballot last month. Of those, 2,072 backed strike action and 809 opposed
it. The ballot was carried out by an independent organisation - Electoral
Reform Balloting Services.
A 24-hour strike planned for last Friday was called off when it became clear
that notification of the strike had not specified the exact period of the
action. The union's lawyers advised the executive to make the period covered
by the stoppage more precise.
Mr Bob Crow, a leading leftwing member of the RMT executive, has been
elected one of the union's three assistant general secretaries. He ousted Mr
Tony McGregor by 2-1 in a ballot of members.
</TEXT>
