<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / InterCity aims to woo lost travellers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
InterCity is to offer 25,000 free tickets to rail travellers on November 8
and 9 in a competition aimed at winning back customers lost during the
16-week signal workers' strike.
Seats will be offered on the six long-distance InterCity routes covering 140
destinations from Penzance to Inverness and about 2,000 miles of railway
travel.
The InterCity companies - Great Western, East Coast, Cross Country, Midland
Main Line, West Coast and Anglia - lost Pounds 53m in revenues, a quarter of
the total loss suffered by the entire rail network.
Other parts of the British Rail network are also considering special
promotions involving free or discounted tickets to attract people back to
the railway. South West Trains said it was looking at a similar promotion
while South Eastern said it was planning a campaign to boost travel.
Mr Andrew Harvey, InterCity marketing manager, said the Pounds 1m promotion
was 'a way to encourage customers who were forced into seeking other means
of transport to come back to the railway, and our way of saying thank you to
customers for putting up with the disruption throughout the dispute'.
Up to 250,000 people are expected to take part in the competition, which
will be advertised in the press. They will be asked to answer a question and
fill in a coupon giving their choice of destination and day and time of
travel.
InterCity denied that seats would be offered only on trains which nobody
wanted to travel on and said all InterCity services would be on offer,
including every Pullman service. There will, however, be quotas on the most
popular trains.
The free seats are being offered on a Tuesday and Wednesday because
InterCity offers its fullest service in the week. This may exclude many
commuters because they will be at work.
</TEXT>
