<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / Rival group may challenge milk levy plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A rival milk group threatened yesterday to launch a legal challenge to the
Milk Marketing Board if it went ahead with plans to charge Britain's 28,000
dairy farmers up to 4p per litre to provide the funding for market
liberalisation in November.
Mr Richard Smith, chairman of the Northern Milk Partnership, which
represents a group of farmers who have agreed to sell their milk to Northern
Foods in the new free market, said he was examining ways in which any
attempt to deduct money from his members could be resisted through the UK
and European courts.
Mr Smith, who has written in protest to Mr William Waldegrave, agriculture
minister, called by the Milk Marketing Board suggestion of the levy
'astonishing and, if implemented, nothing short of disgraceful'.
The milk board needs about Pounds 30m to wind up its operations and
establish Milk Marque, the voluntary farmers' co-operative that will succeed
it.
It said yesterday that the probability of the levy being imposed was minute,
but that it had to have funds to hand should guarantees from its banks not
come through in time for market deregulation on November 1.
But all farmers would be expected to pay the levy, even if they had no plans
to join Milk Marque. Mr Smith said it was 'iniquitous' that the 30 per cent
of producers who had made alternative arrangements for selling their milk
should be forced to pay. He said it would cost his members about Pounds
2,000 each.
The National Farmers' Union said it was extremely concerned about the
possibility that the money would not be repaid. Sir David Naish, union
president, is to meet Mr Bob Steven, chairman of the board, on Monday to
discuss the issue.
The board needs to raise cash to finance the market's deregulation because
the flotation of its processing arm, Dairy Crest, has been delayed.
Mr Andrew Dare, chief executive of the board, said farmers who had not
signed up with Milk Marque should still be prepared to pay the levy as it
would guarantee the free market going ahead from November 1 which was in
everyone's interests.
</TEXT>
