<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / Persil Power 'no better than others': Unilever rejects
report in new round of soap wars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Persil Power, Unilever's controversial detergent, is no better overall at
removing stains from clothes than other soap powders such as Novon Colour,
Sainsbury's own-label brand, and Procter &amp; Gamble's Ariel Ultra, the
Consumers' Association said yesterday.
Ms Helen Parker, acting editor of Which?, the association's magazine, said
that although the powder was good at removing some stains such as red wine,
like other detergents, it was much less effective against difficult stains
such as curry. Which? magazine carries a report on Persil Power in its
latest issue.
Unilever rejected the report. It said: 'The Consumers' Association is not a
test institute. It is trying to work in a very complex situation. Tests by
independent research laboratories show Persil Power is superior.'
The detergent, which Unilever has promoted as the biggest breakthrough in a
generation in cleaning power, has sparked controversy because of allegations
that its patented manganese catalyst, the 'accelerator', can damage clothes
under certain conditions.
Soon after the launch of Persil Power the volume of 'accelerator' in the
detergent was reduced by Unilever.
The Consumers' Association tested the original version in June and the
latest version last month and found no difference between them in cleaning
power.
Ms Parker said: 'If you were worried that you were missing out on a
revolution in stain-busting because of the controversy over Persil Power,
then rest easy. Our independent tests show that the stain-removing ability
of new Persil Power is no better than that of some of its rival brands and
own-brands.'
The association said that its tests for potential damage by Persil Power to
clothes will not be completed for several months.
The Dutch consumers' association concluded three weeks ago that Omo Power,
the version of the detergent sold on the Continent, was no better at stain
removal than other detergents. Moreover, the damage it caused clothes was
'more than comparable powders'.
Unilever gained support yesterday, however, from the Danish consumers'
association, which was quoted as saying: 'There is no acute problem and we
do not advise against Omo Power. If the detergent damages the garments, it
will be a long-term effect.'
The association also said it did not know whether other detergents had the
same long-term effects because 'no other detergent has been tested as
thoroughly as Omo Power'.
Each negative report has hit Unilever's sales of the detergent, particularly
in the Netherlands and Britain where press coverage has been heaviest.
Unilever stood by its claims for the cleaning prowess of the latest Persil
Power. It said: 'The Consumers' Association's results are based on
laboratory testing. What we have always said is that it is what happens in
homes that counts.'
</TEXT>
