<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Post sell-off 'without any
public support'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday delayed a decision on privatising the Post Office
as Labour warned that it would put the fight to keep the corporation public
at the forefront of its attack on the Tories.
The conference unanimously voted for a motion opposing privatisation and
calling for the Post Office to remain in the public sector with more
commercial freedom. Downing Street said today's cabinet meeting was unlikely
to make a decision on whether to press ahead with flotation of the Royal
Mail. This followed contacts between Mr John Major and Mr Richard Ryder,
chief whip, on the implications of Post Office privatisation.
Although the consultative period over the Post Office's future ended last
week, government officials said the Department of Trade and Industry needed
more time to work through all the responses.
They suggested that Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, may
make no announcement on the Post Office's future at next week's Conservative
party conference in Bournemouth.
Mr Heseltine, strongly backed by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, would
like to make a quick decision in favour of selling off 51 per cent of Royal
Mail. Any delay is likely to undermine their efforts to press ahead with the
privatisation.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry spokesman, yesterday told his
party's conference in Blackpool that the people who used the Post Office
wanted it to remain public instead of being turned into someone else's
business.
He said: 'If the government cannot persuade the people who use the Post
Office to privatise it, ministers have no right to ask the House of Commons
to pass a bill to privatise it.'
Mr Cook recalled that Baroness Thatcher, former prime minister, had drawn
back from privatising the Post Office because of public feeling. 'I warn
Michael Heseltine, John Major and the cabinet: People still feel very
strongly about keeping the Post Office in the public sector.'
He said Labour would put the fight to keep the corporation public in the
forefront of its attack on the government when the Commons resumes next
month.
Mr Derek Hodgson, deputy general secretary of the UCW postal workers' union,
attacked Post Office management for promoting privatisation. 'They are a
disgrace,' he said. 'The Post Office does not need to be exposed to the
ravages of money-grabbing speculators.'
After the debate the Post Office said: 'It is misleading scaremongering to
talk about post office closures and loss of services. Whatever happens, the
post office network will stay in the public sector, with a firm commitment
that it remains a nationwide service.'
</TEXT>
