<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Leadership faces defeat on
defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair is today expected to face his first defeat at the Labour
conference - on a renewed demand for the scrapping of the Trident missile
system.
Advocates of nuclear disarmament disregarded an appeal by Mr Neil Kinnock,
in his final speech as a member of the party's national executive committee,
to reject the resolution. They demanded a card vote.
The resolution, which also calls for Britain's defence spending to be cut to
the level of other countries in western Europe, is likely to be approved.
Ironically, Mr Kinnock's emotional speech was accorded a standing ovation.
In it he expressed his gratitude for having been given a 'mandate' when he
was Labour leader to change the party's unilateralist policy on nuclear
disarmament.
Delegates laughed and cheered when Mr Kinnock told them: 'Our relationship
has not, on all occasions, been marked by peace, and light and mutual
admiration.'
Mr Kinnock, who will soon take up his post as a European commissioner in
Brussels, said he would regret to his dying day his failure to lead the
party to victory. Labour's defeat in the 1992 general election had been a
tragedy for the country 'because it extended the years of injustice, waste
and lost opportunities'.
Now the party had a new opportunity and, after Mr Blair's first conference
speech as party leader, the country knew that he could be trusted with the
power of government.
Urging the conference to reject the demand to scrap Trident, Mr Kinnock
underlined the need to keep the trust of the people. He warned that the
weakening of Britain's ability to defend itself would also jeopardise the
chance of further action to achieve mutual and balanced reductions of all
armaments.
</TEXT>
