FT  06 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Pledges 'would cost Pounds
11.5bn'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In the first two days of its annual conference Labour made commitments which
will increase annual public spending by more than Pounds 11.5bn, according
to the Conservatives.
In contrast to the view at the Blackpool gathering that Labour has not made
specific commitments, Tory researchers claimed they had already found Pounds
11.57bn worth of Labour spending pledges.
Publishing its Labour Spendometer, the Conservative Research Department said
it had totalled all spending promises made in conference motions that the
National Executive Committee was supporting, and in speeches by
frontbenchers during the first two days of the conference.
The Tory document states that a fixed statutory minimum wage at half median
male earnings - or just over Pounds 4 an hour - would add about Pounds 1.5bn
a year to the public-sector pay bill.
It did not refer to Mr Tony Blair's refusal to commit Labour to fixing a
firm figure before the general election.
