<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Shadow cabinet braced for a
radical shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair's dramatic conference promise to deliver rapid change has
fuelled hopes among supporters that he is planning a wide-ranging shadow
cabinet shake-up.
Mr Blair is believed to be unhappy with the composition of the shadow
cabinet - elected by Labour MPs at the start of each parliamentary year -
and is said to be keen to keep up the momentum of change.
He has made no changes since succeeding John Smith as party leader in July
and is said to regard the elections as an opportunity to speed up the pace
of party modernisation.
Friends point out that he has already moved to replace Mr Larry Whitty, the
traditionalist general secretary, who will take up a new job as European
co-ordinator later this year. Nominations for the job closed on Tuesday. Mr
Tom Sawyer, a close union ally of Mr Blair, is regarded as certain to be
appointed.
Mr Blair's freedom to reshape the shadow cabinet will depend on the election
results, to be announced later this month. Mr Blair and Mr John Prescott,
the deputy leader, will sit on the shadow cabinet as of right, creating two
election vacancies.
Some members, notably Mr Derek Foster, the chief whip, believe that they
have secured sufficient nominations to be certain of survival.
Senior shadow ministers say that several members are at risk, however,
opening the way for fresh
These include Mr Jack Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, and Mr Tom
Clarke, shadow overseas development minister, who are thought to have made
insufficient impact. Some MPs say that the two men are threatened by the
breakdown of an informal electoral pact between Scottish and north-eastern
MPs which has previously increased the prospects of candidates from those
regions.
Mr Blair is expected to demote Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary,
who is regarded as uninspiring. He is thought likely to promote Mr Chris
Smith, the environment spokesman, and Ms Marjorie Mowlam, a close ally who
failed this week to achieve election to the ruling national executive
committee.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, is regarded as a strong
candidate to replace Mr Cunningham and Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment
secretary, is tipped to replace Mr Prescott at employment. Mrs Margaret
Beckett, the former deputy leader, is certain to be elected and will be
offered a senior role such as the home office, employment or trade and
industry.
Ms Harriet Harman, shadow chief secretary, is expected to do well after
performing more strongly this year. Ms Harman lost her place last year after
failing to dent Mr Michael Portillo, the then chief secretary to the
Treasury.
Several newcomers are also expected to do well, including Ms Hilary
Armstrong, who was Mr Smith's parliamentary private secretary.
MPs said that Mr Kevin McNamara, a co-opted member who serves as shadow
Northern Ireland secretary, was likely to survive, in spite of speculation
that he would lose his job, after backing Mr Blair's shift away from
Labour's commitment to campaigning for a united Ireland.
Others regarded as good outside bets include Mr Brian Wilson, a junior
transport spokesman, and Mr Alastair Darling, the City spokesman. Ms Joyce
Quin, who speaks on European affairs, may also win substantial support.
</TEXT>
