<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / Albania stops second exodus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DURRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
More than 15,000 Albanians have been prevented from attempting to flee the
country aboard ships at the Adriatic port of Durres, the authorities said. A
police official in Durres said groups of young people had tried to make
their way to the port area of the town, about 30km west of Tirana, in what
looked like a repeat of an exodus in 1991 when thousands crammed on to ships
to flee to Italy. Police said special forces had blocked roads entering
Durres from the south and east, turning back about 15,000 Albanians in the
last three days. Those turned away mostly came from the towns of Elbasani,
Librazhdi, Fieri and Lushnja. Young people caught by police said they had
heard rumours the port would open and ferries would be leaving for Italy.
More than 20,000 Albanians tried to flee the country on ships in March and
August 1991, following the collapse of 40 years of hardline communist rule.
Most of them left on rusting ships moored in Durres for Bari and Brindisi in
Italy. Italian authorities sent most of them back.
</TEXT>
