<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / FT Exporter (22): Sales are up but jobs numbers fall -
Analysis / Review of the FT's latest list of Top 100 UK Exporters and finds
that there has been little movement among leading companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The improvement in the world economy, the growing competitiveness in some
sectors of UK industry, and the 1992 devaluation of sterling left many of
the top British exporters enjoying strong sales growth abroad last year.
However, the FT's latest survey of leading exporters suggests that the
overall growth in exports did not lead to much job creation within the UK,
with most of the more successful exporters reducing workforces during the
year in an attempt to achieve greater productivity.
Overall, the survey indicates that there has been little significant
movement in the ranking of top exporters, with foreign-owned companies still
representing a large proportion of the export table.
The rankings of the three largest exporters, British Aerospace, British
Petroleum and Shell UK, remain unchanged amid good export growth. Together
they account for about a quarter of the total export sales of the top 100.
Shell and British Petroleum benefited from a strong performance in the North
Sea oil and gas sector, boosted in recent months by a number of new fields
coming on stream. A spokesman for BP said: 'The main growth has come from
oil and gas - it's mostly down to the North Sea.'
Further down the table, the rankings showed more change. Zeneca, which
entered the top 100 in 1992, after Imperial Chemicals Industry hived off its
bioscience subsidiary, turned in an extremely healthy export performance.
The group jumped from 10th to seventh place, with a 19.4 per cent increase
in exports during the year.
Mr Steve Mayo, finance director at Zeneca, said that the company was
'extremely proud' of its export contribution. Although the group's main
markets were still the US and Europe, increasing sales in the Far East and
Latin America had contributed to the export growth, he said. However, he
pointed out that the company's performance overall appeared to be flattered
by the export figures themselves, because the total actual sales increase
during the year had been slightly lower, at about 12 per cent, than the
growth in exports. 'This is probably a better guide to the underlying
performance,' he added.
ICI fared slightly worse, slipping from seventh to ninth place during the
year, with only a 4.3 per cent growth in exports. Meanwhile, Ford Motors,
the UK market leader in the vehicle sector, fell to eighth from fourth. The
drop partly reflected difficult trading conditions in Europe's car market,
with Ford's exports to Europe falling by 24.4 per cent in the year. Although
Nissan Motors largely shrugged off these problems, showing a 6.9 per cent
export growth into Europe during the year, the European recession also
affected Vauxhall, where exports fell by 44.9 per cent. The drop dragged
Vauxhall's ranking down to 31 from 15.
One star performer in the table, however, was Compaq, the US-owned computer
group which has been rapidly building its market share in Europe after
establishing production sites in Scotland seven years ago. The group leapt
from 25th to 13th during the year, on the back of an impressive 113 per cent
increase in exports. Most of this growth was targeted on Europe, where
exports rose by 138.8 per cent as the company benefited not only from
increased demand for portable computers but also from a greater market
share. After being ranked as the fourth largest PC supplier in Europe in
1992, Compaq is now estimated to have the largest share of the European
market, after being number two last year.
This growth in the computer market appears to have benefited other
companies, such as International Business Machines.
Overall, however, the table does not indicate particularly strong sectoral
trends. Although the UK's strength in the world chemicals industry was
underlined by good performances from companies such as Glaxo, the star
performers among the smaller companies came from a range of industries.
British American Tobacco, for example, saw exports grow by 30 per cent,
primarily as a result of expansion into Asian and other non-European
markets. Marks &amp; Spencer, the retailers, saw exports grow by 21.9 per cent,
pushing the company up from 56th to 27th in the rankings.
One theme that does emerge from the table is that with Europe in deep
recession during most of 1993, much of the strongest growth came from
markets outside the European Union, particularly in the US and Far East.
Hillsdown, the food producer, for example, saw exports grow by 21.2 per cent
overall, but fall by 1.8 per cent in Europe. Thorn EMI saw a similar
pattern, with a 2 per cent growth in overall exports and a 7 per cent fall
in European markets. Meanwhile, Vosper Thorneycroft, the defence contractor,
saw exports grow by 35.2 per cent in the year, but fall by 5.9 per cent in
Europe.
Mr Martin Jay, managing director at Vosper Thorneycroft, said that the
strongest export markets had been in the Middle East and Gulf. 'In the past
five years we have increased productivity in steel ships by 50 per cent,' he
said.
Another trend apparent from the survey is that the growth in exports has not
necessarily led to significant job increases. Nearly all of the 15 top
exporters cut their workforce during the year, with the only exception being
Nissan Motors, which is expanding its production in the UK.
The employee cuts were not necessarily related to the export growth. Shell
UK, for example, saw export growth of 25.4 per cent during the year - but
reduced its workforce by 12.3 per cent. At the other end of the spectrum,
Arjo Wiggins reduced its workforce by 7.6 per cent, after achieving 8.4 per
cent export growth in the year.
Some of these cuts may not have reflected redundancies - BP, for example,
points out that its 22.6 per cent reduction in its workforce also reflected
divestment of a number of subsidiaries. However, in many cases they suggest
that companies are continuing to seek increasingly high levels of
productivity on which to base any future export growth.
</TEXT>
<XX>
