<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / FT Exporter (1): New agenda for world trade - Martin Wolf
examines prospects for world trade after the Uruguay Round - the most
complex and ambitious trade negotiation ever attempted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN WOLF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOOKING AHEAD: The ability of the industrial countries to adjust to emerging
giants, such as China and India, must be in question.  If they fail,
protection would probably be the outcome.
From the beginning of next year, world trade is to be overseen by a new
institution, the World Trade Organisation. Forget, for the moment, the fact
that a successor to Mr Peter Sutherland, outgoing Director General of the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, has still to be found. Ignore
nagging doubts about whether the Uruguay Round will be ratified. Despite
everything, it is far more likely than not that the US and European Union
will resolve their internal difficulties and ratify the outcome of their
seven years of hard labour.
What sort of trading scene will the new body have to deal with?
The starting point is the outcome of the Uruguay Round itself. The most
complex and ambitious trade negotiation ever attempted, its completion was a
remarkable and, on balance, hugely beneficial achievement. The commitment to
bringing virtually all aspects of world trade under a single umbrella is
particularly important. Gone is the special status granted for 33 years to
textiles and clothing; gone is the virtual exclusion of agriculture from
international disciplines; gone also is the purely ad hoc approach to the
liberalisation of trade in services.
Perhaps most important of all, there is now an integrated and more effective
system of dispute settlement, something required by any effective
international agreement of this kind. Nor should the trade liberalisation
aspects themselves be ignored. There is, for example, a significant
reduction in the level of tariffs: the average developed-country tariff on
industrial products will fall by almost 40 per cent - from 6.3 to 3.9 per
cent. Large reductions in developing country tariffs are also planned
For all that, as Brian Hindley of the London School of Economics points out
in a review of the round, it leaves some important problems in its wake.*
Among them are:
The potential for confusion if some countries choose to be members of the
original Gatt (Gatt 1947), but not the WTO, while others choose to be
members of the WTO, but not Gatt 1947.
The weak obligations in the General Agreement on Trade in Services and the
limited nature of the commitments to trade liberalisation in services.
The possibly deleterious effects on the developing countries of the strong
protection afforded to intellectual property.
The very limited nature of the liberalisation of trade in agriculture.
The long delays in liberalisation of trade in textiles and clothing, which
is to be completed only by 2005, with most of the meaningful liberalisation
postponed until the last few years.
And, above all, the limited significance of the decision to tighten up on
'grey area measures,' such as voluntary export restraints, particularly
given the failure to discipline the use of anti-dumping measures as a
protectionist device.
The global policy-making community must, however, do more than cope with
what the Uruguay Round failed to do. Already there is a new agenda. One
element in it is trade and the environment, on which a committee was
established at the ministerial meeting in Marrakesh in April. Another issue
being pushed by the Clinton administration, with French support, is trade
and labour standards, a topic as controversial  - and potentially as
threatening, particularly from the developing country point of view - as
trade and the environment.
Also being discussed as potential topics for inclusion in future
negotiations are trade and competition policy and, still more tentatively,
the treatment of investment. In addition, the WTO must negotiate membership
for China, Russia and other former states of the Soviet Union.
All this is the visible face of trade policy. Underneath it, there are two
contrasting trends. Developing countries - long addicted to protectionism,
demands for 'special and differential treatment' and non-reciprocity - have
been liberalising their trade barriers, both unilaterally and within the
context of the Uruguay Round, as is also true of former members of the
Soviet bloc.
More than 60 countries notified the Gatt secretariat of unilateral trade
liberalisation during the course of the Uruguay Round. While these were
mainly developing and former communist countries, their number included
hitherto-protectionist Australia and New Zealand.
Such liberalisation has made trade from - and to - the more outward-looking
developing countries the most dynamic single element in world trade. Between
1981 and 1992, world trade grew at an average annual rate, in real terms, of
5.2 per cent (itself above the rate of growth of world output). But imports
of developing countries in the East Asia and Pacific region grew at 7.8 per
cent a year, while their imports from one another grew at the still more
dramatic average rate of 14.9 per cent a year.
For much of the 1980s, the Latin American developing countries were relative
laggards. But signs of faster growth began to emerge there, too, in the
1990s, in response to policy reform. Thus the volume of regional exports
rose by 7 and 9.5 per cent in 1992 and 1993, respectively, while the volume
of imports went up by 18 and 8 per cent.
Developing countries are looking increasingly outward, so following the
advice long showered upon them by advanced industrial countries. Meanwhile,
many in the latter have become increasingly dubious about the entire idea.
During the course of the Uruguay Round, there emerged powerful protectionist
pressures in industrial countries, as unemployment soared in Europe and the
real wages of unskilled labour fell in the US. The influence of Mr Ross
Perot in the last presidential election is one symptom of this development.
The agitation against the Gatt in France is another.
The academic literature on the effect of trade on wages and employment is
vast and hitherto somewhat inconclusive. Most authors would agree that
changes in technology have been more important for the demand for unskilled
labour than imports from developing countries. But the ability of the
industrial countries to adjust to the emergence of giants, such as China
(already the world's 11th largest exporter) and India, must be in question.
Should they fail, protection would probably be the outcome.
This would then endanger the achievements of the Uruguay Round and even the
WTO. Things would be still worse if, as seems plausible, the developing
countries were to respond in kind. But if the pressure were to be resisted,
the prospect for dynamic growth of exports to developing and former
communist countries should be a golden one. This could even prove the start
of an epoch of trade expansion as dynamic as that of the 1950s and 1960s.
*Brian Hindley, 'Two Cheers for the Uruguay Round,' in Hindley and Deepak
Lal (eds), Trade Policy Review 1994, (London: Centre for Policy Studies,
1994).
</TEXT>
