<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / International Company News: Motorola beats IBM to market
with PowerPC-based machines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Motorola, the US electronics and communications manufacturer, has beaten
International Business Machines, its technology partner, to market with
personal computers based on PowerPC microprocessor chips, jointly developed
by the companies and Apple Computer.
Apple introduced its first 'Power Macintosh' computers incorporating the new
microprocessors earlier this year but IBM postponed its range until next
year.
IBM already offers scientific workstations and multi-user computers based on
PowerPC technology.
Motorola yesterday announced a range of PowerPC computers including desktop
models aimed at the PC market, 'servers' which are used to manage networks
of desktop computers, and multi-user computer systems. The launches mark the
first time that Motorola has entered the high-volume PC market with a
system-level product.
The company said it planned to broaden the computer product line with
systems aimed at departmental and enterprise-wide computing over the next
year.
'The Motorola computer group is committed to becoming the premier source of
a full line of computer systems and single board computers based on the
PowerPC microprocessor,' said Mr Karl Stoltze, vice-president of marketing.
The company aims to sell the computers to third parties, most of whom
relabel them, add software and sell on.
Motorola also disclosed technology agreements with IBM to license that
company's AIX (a version of Unix) computer operating system software, and
with Groupe Bull to license its symmetrical multiprocessing technology. Bull
is expected to be one of Motorola's customers for the new line of computers.
The PowerPC microprocessor is more powerful than competing chips from Intel,
say Motorola and IBM. This makes them well suited to demanding desktop
applications such as multimedia with video and graphics.
However, the new chips lack the broad software base available for
Intel-based PCs. It was this lack of software that led IBM to delay the
launch of its PowerPC personal computers.
</TEXT>
