<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / US group may buy Ulster engineer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A big US company may be about to buy FG Wilson (Engineering), the
Larne-based company which is Europe's largest producer of diesel sets used
for generating electricity.
Privately-held Wilson, one of Northern Ireland's most successful engineering
companies, confirmed yesterday that its directors were in discussions with a
'major American corporation' which had approached it. Wilson would not name
the suitor and said talks were at a preliminary stage. It expected to make a
further statement by today.
Last night, there was strong speculation that Emerson Electric, the US
electrical and electronics product group, would launch a bid for Wilson. A
spokesman for Emerson said he had no information on any bid.
If Wilson is taken over, it would be the second purchase this week of an
independent UK producer of generating sets. Cummins Engine, the US diesel
engine group, is buying Sandwich, Kent-based Power Group International, best
known for its Petbow, Auto Diesel and Agreba brands.
A substantial investment in Wilson would be a major coup for a company
wishing to enter the fast-growing market for diesel generating sets. The
Larne company was founded in 1966, and has grown to achieve annual sales of
more than Pounds 160m and export markets in 120 countries.
It employs about 1,000 people, most of them at Larne. It recently moved into
an old GEC factory there, consolidating manufacturing which used to take
place at five separate facilities.
A link-up with a company such as Emerson, one of the best-known names in the
world electrical products industry, could give Wilson access to a wider
distribution network. Other names mentioned as possible bidders included
Caterpillar, the world's largest construction equipment company, which also
has a power generation business.
At Cummins, Mr James Henderson, president and chief executive, said PGI fit
'right into our product diversification strategy and our goal to achieve
profitable growth in global markets'. Terms were not disclosed, but Cummins
said PGI was profitable and had sales last year of Pounds 59m. It has plants
in the UK and Singapore producing generators ranging from 20KW to 3MW and
more than 400 employees.
</TEXT>
