<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / Gotcha] Mirror Group lures MacKenzie to cable channel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Mirror Group nabbed Kelvin MacKenzie yesterday, hauling on board the
former Sun editor who revelled for years in being rude about his tabloid
competitor.
Mr MacKenzie, with only seven months' television experience under his belt
when he quit BSkyB, the satellite broadcaster, in August, is joining the
Mirror Group to head its budding television interests. They consist of a 20
per cent stake in Scottish Television and the promise to launch Live TV, a
new cable channel, next year.
The man famous for the 'Gotcha' headline on the sinking of the Belgrano
during the Falklands war will report to Mr David Montgomery, Mirror Group's
chief executive and a man over whom he has poured volumes of vitriol since
they parted company at The Sun 13 years ago.
The last time they worked in close proximity was at the Wapping headquarters
of Mr Rupert Murdoch's News International group, where they edited sister
newspapers.
Neither man was available for comment yesterday but they did contribute
consecutive quotes to a press release: 'Kelvin is a major force in the
British media and with his unique background and recent broadcasting
experience will add dynamic leadership to our now well-developed framework
for TV entry,' said Mr Montgomery. Mr MacKenzie, a man of famously pithy and
often unprintable epithets, said: 'This is a terrific challenge and I can't
wait to get on with it.'
But forget the tele-strategy and synergy. Did Kelvin fire David 13 years ago
at The Sun? Mr Sean Bellew, for the Mirror Group, said: 'David says that is
simply not true. He was offered the assistant editorship of The People, so
he left.'
So why is Mr MacKenzie joining the Mirror? 'Kelvin has told me there is only
one reason for life,' said Mr Roy Greenslade, former Sun assistant editor.
'Get Sam Chisholm.'
Mr MacKenzie blamed his departure from BSkyB on a personality clash with Mr
Chisholm, its chief executive. Mr MacKenzie was managing director and,
according to colleagues, thought he would head BSkyB when Mr Chisholm
assumed a broader role in Mr Murdoch's television empire.
Given a common enemy, Mr MacKenzie and Mr Montgomery might be able to work
together, a friend of both said yesterday. 'Kelvin does have a grudging
respect for what David's done at the Mirror,' he said.
Observer, Page 23
                           *      *      *
MacKenzie on the Mirror: 'I feel sorry for a lot of the trees that are cut
down to turn into the Daily Mirror.' (July 1993)
The Mirror on MacKenzie: 'Is this Britain's nastiest boss?' it asked in a
headline above a picture of MacKenzie. (November 1987)
</TEXT>
