<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Ending Clause 4 cuts ties
with past
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The words have been inscribed on every membership card issued by the Labour
party since 1918.
Clause 4 of the party's constitution, committing the party to the 'common
ownership of the means of production, distribution and exchange', is the
symbol of Labour's attachment to a collectivist past.
Mr Tony Blair promised when he was elected as leader to abandon that past.
His call yesterday for a fundamental overhaul of the party's constitution
was the proof of his serious intent.
The terms of the surprise proposal - a call for a clear, up-to-date
statement of the party's objectives instead of a blunt repudiation of Clause
4 - were framed to avoid immediate controversy on the conference floor.
The emphasis deliberately was on the new statement of aims and values which
he will present jointly with Mr John Prescott to the party's national
executive. The conference applauded loudly, although it did not quite know
what it was cheering.
But there was no doubt about Mr Blair's intentions. Labour has abandoned the
pretence that it can run a command economy, that it can re-nationalise the
privatised industries, and that the state knows better than the market.
It is time, the new leader has decided, for the rhetoric of the constitution
to catch up with the reality.
He was confident yesterday that the move will succeed, that he will not
suffer the ignominious defeat inflicted 35 years ago on the then Labour
leader Hugh Gaitskell by the party's traditionalists. Then, Mr Gaitskell's
vain attempt to scrap Clause 4 destroyed his leadership.
Mr Neil Kinnock, the architect of the painful modernisation process which
started in 1983, thought about taking up the fight again before the 1992
general election.
But after forcing the party to abandon the policies which once gave
substance to Clause 4, he judged that a battle over the treasured words
would have been too divi-sive.
Earlier this year Mr Kinnock raised the idea in public. But his successor,
the late John Smith, decided to draw a line under constitutional change
after his bruising battle with the unions over party democracy.
In a party dogged for decades by a culture of struggle and fears of betrayal
by the leadership, many of the traditionalists still regard Clause 4 as the
litmus test of its socialist credentials.
It was clear from the words yesterday of Mr Arthur Scargill, the miners'
leader, that the unreconstructed left will fight Mr Blair as their
predecessors fought Mr Gaitskell. The opponents will win support among the
party's romantics.
The Labour leader has decided that he has no time for such ideological
purity. More importantly, nor do the voters who have kept his party out of
government for 15 years.
He has decided to convince the electorate that Labour really has changed.
As Mr Blair told the delegates in Blackpool: 'This is a modern party living
in an age of change. It requires a modern constitution that says what we are
in terms the public cannot misunderstand and the Tories cannot
misrepresent.'
For all their attachment to the past, most in the party look ready this time
to accept that Mr Blair is right.
</TEXT>
