<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Wooing the bosses with
chablis and canapes - Labour's meeting with business leaders on its first
ever corporate day
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It had all the hallmarks of a Conservative fundraising event. Chief
executives and directors of some of Britain's biggest companies lunching on
chablis and canapes, sponsored by Philip Morris, the tobacco company, which
hired Baroness Thatcher as a consultant.
But there wasn't a Tory in sight - at least none willing to admit it. This
was the Labour party's first ever corporate day.
Ms Nicki Lewis, the party's corporate relations manager, was shepherding
captains of industry around a Blackpool hotel room to meet members of
Labour's shadow cabinet. In case the line-up was not sufficient to attract
the big names in industry, the party boosted its star quality with the
support of Mr David Puttnam, the film producer, and Mr Ken Follett, the
author.
There was little need for the supporting cast. Those attending - dubbed by
one Labour aide as Britain's deserving rich - wanted to meet the men and
women many were convinced would form a Labour cabinet.
Mr John Moores, a director of Littlewoods football pools whose family
controls about 40 per cent of the company's shares, said:  'Since Labour is
going to form the next government, it's worth getting to know them.'
For Pounds 350 per person, the executives - including Sir John Egan, chief
executive of the airports group BAA, Mr Michael Cassidy, chairman of the
Corporation of London's policy committee, and Mr Peter Harper, a director of
Hanson - breakfasted with Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, and Mr
Alistair Darling, the party's City spokesman.
There were also senior representatives from Tesco, the food retailer, and
Motorola, the electronics company.
The executives lunched with some of the party's most senior MPs before being
ferried back to their VIP balcony in Blackpool's Winter Gardens to hear Mr
Tony Blair give his first speech as Labour Leader.
While leftwing delegates were muttering betrayal over Mr Blair's
thinly-veiled attack on Clause 4 of the constitution, the executives were in
face-to-face conversation with the Labour leader at a drinks party he hosted
at the Imperial Hotel on the seafront.
They also sat down to a sumptuous dinner with Mr John Prescott, deputy
leader.
Not all those attending Labour's first corporate day viewed the proceedings
with unalloyed enthusiasm. Mr Cassidy was disappointed that Mr Brown did not
set out his policies or strategy for business in more detail. He also had a
blunt message for his Labour hosts - if Mr Brown's attack on the
'undeserving rich' leads to punitive taxes on foreigners, it will jeopardise
the future of the City which the corporation estimates contributes Pounds
8bn a year to the British economy.
Mr Harper of Hanson, one of the biggest corporate donors to the Conservative
party, feared his hosts had not sufficiently understood his arguments that
high dividends did not restrict investment.
'They also don't seem to understand that takeovers of companies act as a
great discipline on managers.'
But Mr Harper was delighted that he was being listened to at all. As was Sir
John, who said: 'As a privatised company we have a case to prove that we are
able to continue to generate wealth and it is encouraging that Labour want
to listen to it.'
Most companies were there for practical reasons. Mr Cassidy said: 'With only
two-and-a-half years to go to the next election Labour is ahead in the polls
by around 27 per cent.'
</TEXT>
