FT  05 OCT 94 / Avon rejects transition costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Avon County Council yesterday made a further attempt to avoid abolition
under the local government review, saying that the transitional costs of
reorganisation had been greatly underestimated.
The local government commission has recommended that the county and six
district councils in Avon should be replaced by four unitary authorities. In
June the High Court rejected an application by the county for a judicial
review of the proposals.
An Avon deputation including councillors from all three political parties
and backed by local business groups and trade unions yesterday urged Mr
David Curry, local government minister, to reject the proposals and refer
them back to the commission.
The deputation told Mr Curry that the commission's estimate of Pounds 16m in
transitional costs in Avon made no allowance for redundancy payments. The
district councils estimated the costs at up to Pounds 34m, and the county
council at about Pounds 40m.
Avon council also said that the commission's proposals would not provide the
strategic capacity to tackle the region's economic development, transport
and planning.
