<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / TGWU to probe fraud allegations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Transport and General Workers' Union has launched an inquiry into the
running of its north-west England region after allegations of fraud and
wrongful financial accounting in its Merseyside divisional office.
Mr Bill Morris, TGWU general secretary, said yesterday that 'major fraud'
had been discovered and the TGWU was taking action to see that it did not
happen again. He added that the union had decided not to call in the police.
The union's executive has agreed to set up a four-man inquiry to decide what
can be done to prevent a repetition of the alleged abuses.
The decision comes in the wake of a report by Mr Albert Blyghton, the
union's legal secretary, following complaints and allegations made against
TGWU officials on Merseyside. Two of three officials named in the report
have already accepted disciplinary action and the other has resigned.
The TGWU general secretary gave the executive a full report of Mr Blyghton's
findings, which conclude that there is 'clear evidence that a major fraud
has been committed against the union and its members in the Merseyside
divisional office, for at least six years.'
The charges include the alleged misuse of members' strike pay by officials,
irregularities in the running of executive council elections and misuse of
finance during recruitment campaigns.
Members told the inquiry in written statements that they had not received
strike pay from the union when involved in five separate disputes on
Merseyside. Other, unknown, people had signed receipts for the money in
their names. The union's auditors had been unable to confirm where the money
had gone.
Mr Blyghton found 'some evidence of financial irregularities' in the
activities of membership recruitment teams organised from the TGWU's
Merseyside divisional office.
It is also alleged that money was misappropriated in a scheme under which a
company supplying illuminated advertising for taxis paid money to the TGWU
on Merseyside to have its signs carried by the union's taxi-driver
membership in the area.
Under the deal Cab Tops, the company, paid the TGWU 'an agreed sum'. The
union would then deduct union contributions and administration charges and
pass the balance to the cab drivers.
Mr Morris said: 'The management of the finances of this scheme were most
irregular. Money paid to the TGWU by Cab Tops was passed through the
Merseyside account into a private building society account'.
It is alleged that a union official who was sole signatory of that account,
'wrote cheques to himself for sums around Pounds 300 and would draw the
money in cash'.
Mr Blyghton also found alleged evidence of financial irregularities in the
use of the union's education budget. There had been no fraud, but 'it was an
example of deliberate wrongful accounting', the report said.
</TEXT>
