FT  05 OCT 94 / Car part suppliers warned on Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's motor component makers were warned yesterday that their Japanese
rivals were improving quality and productivity at more than twice the
average rate in the UK.
They were told at a seminar backed by the Department of Trade and Industry
that most British suppliers would never catch up with the Japanese unless
they made 'fundamental changes' to their practices.
The companies have been taking part in a DTI 'learning from Japan'
initiative. Teams of executives have been in Japan studying the work
practices of the Japanese.
As part of the initiative the performances of the Japanese and British
components sectors are being evaluated by Andersen Consulting.
Ms Betty Thayer, the Andersen Consulting partner most closely involved with
the initiative, told suppliers: 'On average, world-class Japanese suppliers
are improving their performance by more than 50 per cent a year compared to
less than 25 per cent on average (for the UK industry).'
The aim of the two-year initiative, started earlier this year and backed by
Rover Group and Inchcape, is to upgrade nearly 10,000 smaller British
components makers. They
form one of the biggest elements in the economy, with turnover estimated at
Pounds 15bn a year, nearly 150,000 employees and exports of Pounds 3bn.
</TEXT>
