<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / Adams benefits from shadow-boxing: The Sinn Fein chief's
warmer-than-expected welcome in Washington
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Clinton administration this weekend decided to salve Mr Gerry Adams's
pride and salvage his two-week tour of the US with a last-minute upgrade in
the level of its contacts with him.
Until last Friday the Sinn Fein leader had been scheduled to meet the State
Department's director of the office of Northern European affairs, and to
'bump into' Ms Nancy Soderberg, staff director of the White House National
Security Council, at a dinner party hosted by the Washington correspondent
of the Irish Times.
But after Mr Adams balked at this relatively low level of meeting his US
sponsors, led by Mr Edward Kennedy, the Democrat senator, increased the
pressure on the White House to accord Mr Adams a more effusive reception.
While sticking to the letter of its promise to the British government that
there would be no meeting at the White House and no meeting with Mr Bill
Clinton, the president, Mr Al Gore, the vice-president, or Mr Anthony Lake,
the national security adviser, the White House obliged.
Mr Adams's State Department host was upgraded to deputy assistant secretary
Mr John Kornblum. Ms Soderberg and Mr Leon Fuerth, the vice-president's
national security adviser, were added to this formal meeting and Mr Lake
conveyed the decision in a gushing letter that had British officials
snorting with annoyance at its praise for Mr Adams as a 'harbinger of
peace.'
To cap it all, the White House decided that Mr Gore would announce the
ending of a 25-year-old US policy barring official contacts with Sinn Fein
in a telephone call to the home of Mrs Ethel Kennedy, widow of the late Mr
Robert widow of the late Mr Robert Kennedy, where Mr Adams was staying.
A senior administration official said: 'We felt this was a fairly historic
decision, and a decision of that level should come from the vice-president.'
Mr Adams's need for a symbolic victory had been increased by the moderate
success of the early part of his US tour.
Before Monday's phone call the view in Whitehall was that the Sinn Fein
president's visit had been much less successful than feared - certainly in
comparison with his ground-breaking trip to New York in February when he was
front-page news.
Events in Haiti and the OJ Simpson trial did not keep the Sinn Fein
president off the air and front pages in the UK as they did in the US.
But when he did hit the headlines - as in the wake of his veiled threat of a
return of IRA violence and the encounter on BBC TV's Newsnight with Mr
Michael Mates, cast in the role of government emissary - the coverage tended
to be critical.
After his hectoring and argumentative performance in the debate with Mr
Mates the impression started to form in London that this period of intense
media exposure - following a six-year spell when Sinn Fein voices were
banned from the airwaves - had quite simply found Mr Adams out.
There was a feeling that one of the most enduring results of his visit would
be to undermine Sinn Fein's image as a ruthlessly efficient propaganda
machine.
Ironically, Fleet Street's news agenda came to London's assistance in the
wake of Washington's decision to open relations with Sinn Fein. The Labour
party conference and a sensational royal story helped to ensure it was
covered less prominently than might otherwise have been the case.
The final verdict on Mr Adams's success in influencing American public
opinion was expected ultimately to hinge on his performance last night in a
30-minute televised debate with Mr Ken Maginnis, the Ulster Unionist
security spokesman.
Although British officials sought publicly to play down the impact of
Washington's diplomatic upgrades, arguing that Mr Clinton had stuck to his
promise not to allow a White House meeting, private reactions have been much
more caustic.
The upgrades probably say less about US policy towards Sinn Fein, or even
about the political clout of Mr Adams's sponsors, than they do about the
weakness of the Clinton administration in general, and on foreign policy in
particular.
They will do nothing to dispel the view prevailing among the US's allies
that the president remains incapable of making and sticking to a decision.
Nevertheless, they have reinforced suspicions that the US is seeking not
just to support the peace process but to play a role in steering it.
'This administration needs to be careful in its contacts with Northern
Ireland,' warned Dr John Alderdice of the Alliance party, whose visit to
Washington coincided with Mr Adams's. Dr Alderdice was received at a higher
level - by Mr Peter Tarnoff, the State Department's number three official.
US officials deny any intention of interfering. But the White House has
alarmed some in Northern Ireland and in the British government by promising
to continue its dialogue with Sinn Fein through its consulate general in
Belfast and its embassy in Dublin - where yet another member of the Kennedy
clan, Mrs Jean Kennedy Smith, is US ambassador.
There is talk of another high-level Sinn Fein visit in November, and
administration officials have even refused to say that they would continue
to refuse visas to members of the IRA.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
    NEWS  General News.
</TP>
