<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / C&amp;G faces fight on compensation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester building society faces the possibility of a legal
battle with the Investors Compensation Scheme over millions of pounds paid
by the ICS to home income plan investors.
The ICS, a scheme for clients of authorised investment firms which have
collapsed, said yesterday that it had rescinded an agreement with C &amp; G in
September 1992, under which C &amp; G paid the ICS Pounds 545,000 and the ICS
agreed not to press for more. ICS had the option of rescinding within two
years.
The scheme, which is funded by a levy on authorised investment firms, said
yesterday that it 'now takes the view that the society's original payment is
not sufficient' but has not suggested another figure. It said the way for
legal proceedings against the society was now open, should it decide that
this is the most appropriate course.
The ICS has paid out Pounds 5.5m to 242 investors who took out home income
plans on the advice of Aylesbury Associates, a firm of independent financial
advisers which went into liquidation in 1992. The mortgages were arranged by
C &amp; G.
It is believed that the ICS may have to pay between Pounds 7m and Pounds 10m
in compensation to wronged Aylesbury Associate investors. The bill may be
even higher if the ICS fails in its appeal to the House of Lords against an
Appeal Court decision ordering it to pay enhanced compensation to home
income plan victims.
Trade Indemnity, the trade credit insurance company which insured the ICS's
liabilities from 1990 to 1992, made an additional Pounds 7.5m provision in
its half-year accounts against further claims.
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester, the target of a Pounds 1.8bn takeover bid by Lloyds
bank, said yesterday that it had made the Pounds 545,000 payment  - which
has been returned with interest - to help speed up payments to those
entitled to them.
It said: 'We were the lender, we did not make the investments. If the ICS
feels it has a case which would stand up in court, OK. That's up to them to
prove it.'
Home income plans were widely sold during the housing boom of the late 1980s
to elderly householders who mortgaged their homes to release capital which
they invested in income bonds. These were meant to pay the interest on the
mortgage and provide an income. Some plans used roll-up mortgages, which
added the interest to the total debt.
This type of home income plan has now been banned because of its riskiness.
</TEXT>
