<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / Housing recovery hopes damped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A significant recovery in the housing market is very unlikely before the
spring, according to the Halifax Building society, which releases its house
price index today.
The Halifax says even a recovery in spring 'will require some upturn in
general consumer confidence which is not helped by speculation about higher
interest rates. The housing market now needs a reasonable period of
stability in interest rates.' Most lenders have increased mortgage rates,
following last month's rise in base rates to 5.75 per cent.
According to the Halifax house prices rose by a seasonally adjusted 0.1 per
cent in September. That small rise contrasts with the 2.9 per cent fall
recorded by the Nationwide Building Society's rival index, released on
Monday.
The two indices have often diverged but neither has shown much sign of a
housing market recovery this year. While the Nationwide reports that house
prices have risen by 1.4 per cent in the 12 months to September, Halifax
records a 0.7 per cent fall in the same period.
Meanwhile, mortgage lending grew slightly in August, according to figures
released by the Bank of England. Gross lending by banks and building
societies was a seasonally adjusted Pounds 4.58bn in August, compared with
Pounds 4.54bn in July.
</TEXT>
