<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / Clarke holds out hope of tax cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, yesterday held out the prospect of tax
cuts but insisted that they would only come when the economy and public
finances were in good health.
In his speech to the annual meeting of the International Monetary Fund and
World Bank, Mr Clarke repeated that talk of tax cuts in November's budget
'is hopelessly premature'.
But he added: 'As the economy strengthens further and public expenditure is
brought firmly under control, tax cuts can come back on to the agenda.'
Mr Clarke warned, however, that the stock of debt in the UK was already far
too high. 'I have no intention of adding to that stock by more than I have
to. Therefore, tax cuts can only take place and will only take place in the
context of healthy recovery and healthy public finances.'
The chancellor stressed that it was 'a matter of judgment' to decide when
tax cuts would help to sustain economic growth rather than impair it.
Mr Clarke admitted to journalists that he was already thinking ahead to his
speech to next week's Tory party conference.
Taking a swipe at the Labour party, he told a press conference that his
speech was to show Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, that there were
economic policies that lay 'between post-classical economic theory on the
one hand and meaningless empty ramblings on the other'.
In a move to deter speculation that the PSBR is falling faster than
forecast, he revised the written version of the IMF speech that was released
in Madrid and London. Whereas the text spoke of a budget deficit 'set to
exceed Pounds 30bn this year' Mr Clarke said the figure should be Pounds
36bn, and so in line with the Treasury's forecast.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
