<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / Canada to unveil radical social security blueprint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Canada's Liberal government will today unveil a blueprint for overhauling a
panoply of generous but costly and increasingly ineffective social security
programmes. The proposals are likely to unleash a debate to test the
government's resolve against a plethora of special interest groups, and its
commitment to cutting the budget deficit.
In an effort to contain the political backlash and retain room for
manoeuvre, Mr Lloyd Axworthy, human resources minister, will present the
proposals in the form of a 'discussion paper'. He plans to introduce
detailed legislation next spring.
A government official said the options would reflect a new direction: 'Our
main aim is to see if we can move the public debate to a different place.'
The Liberals recognise they will be unable to meet their goal of cutting the
federal budget deficit to 3 per cent of GDP without trimming social security
outlays. The programmes in question now cost about CDollars 39bn (Pounds
18.30bn) a year, a third of total federal spending.
They include unemployment insurance, job training, child tax benefits and
transfers to the 10 provinces to fund welfare assistance and post-secondary
education. Old-age pensions will not be included in the review.
Agreement is widespread on the need to reform the social security net, many
components of which have been unchanged for the past three decades. Concern
centres on the growing group of able-bodied people who have fallen into a
'welfare trap' because of generous social security.
Unemployment insurance and social assistance payments now equal 4 per cent
of GNP against less than 1 per cent in the mid-1960s. The number of people
living below the poverty line has risen steadily. Leaks from Ottawa suggest
Mr Axworthy will propose targeting benefits more narrowly, creating
incentives to encourage people to look for work or acquire new skills.
The discussion paper is expected to suggest a clampdown on workers in such
seasonal industries as fishing and construction, who can claim generous
unemployment benefits after as little as 12 weeks' work. The government this
week unveiled a programme to top up the income of people who accept menial
jobs at minimum wages as a way of re-entering the workforce.
Mr Axworthy hopes to defuse criticism of the cuts with a proposal to divert
some savings from lower unemployment insurance and welfare payments to
support under-privileged children. The paper is also expected to propose
reforms in higher education funding, by replacing direct grants to
universities with more generous student loans.
The overhaul will be complicated by split responsibilities between the
federal government and the provinces.
Quebec's new separatist government has indicated it will not take part in
the process unless it considers the reforms to be to its own advantage.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CAZ  Canada.
</CN>
