<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / Senate confirms nominee for FDIC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton won a small victory yesterday, after weeks of
deadlock with Congress on different issues, when the Senate finally voted to
confirm his nominee to head the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation,
writes George Graham in Washington.
The FDIC has been without a chairman since the death of Mr William Taylor
two years ago. The nomination of Ms Ricki Tigert, a Washington lawyer and
former Federal Reserve official, had been held up for 11 months by the
objections of Senator Lauch Faircloth of North Carolina.
Seven Republicans joined 56 Democrats in the Senate to give the 60 vote
majority needed to override Senator Faircloth's filibuster attempt. In a
second vote on the nomination, the Senate confirmed Ms Tigert by 90 to 7.
Mr Faircloth and Senator Alphonse d'Amato had criticised Ms Tigert for being
too closely tied to Mr and Mrs Clinton, and had already compelled her to
promise to step aside from any FDIC involvement in the Whitewater
investigation. This involves the Clintons' investment in an Arkansas
property venture and its links to a federally insured savings institution.
Democratic supporters of Ms Tigert said she was merely a Clinton
acquaintance.
</TEXT>
