<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 94 / IMF/World Bank in Madrid: Ecuador signs deal on debt of
Dollars 7.8bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ecuador yesterday signed an agreement with about 300 private creditors, led
by international banks, to restructure its Dollars 7.8bn (Pounds 5bn) of
external commercial debt.
About 99 per cent of creditors, in a deal that coincided with the IMF
meeting in Madrid, agreed to terms offered in June. Sir David Walker, deputy
chairman of Lloyds Bank, which led the negotiating committee of banks,
called for Ecuador to allow its creditors to take part in a forthcoming
privatisation programme through equity swaps.
Among the largest creditors agreeing to the restructuring was the Dart
family of the US, which acquired its debt in the secondary market. The Darts
are suing Brazil in the US courts over its debt restructuring. One banker
said Ecuador had been more successful in dealing with private creditors such
as the Darts because 'it was aware that it was dealing with more than banks,
and it was careful to maintain a dialogue'.
The Dollars 2.5bn of past due interest which has accumulated on the
principal debt will be repaid by Ecuador issuing 20-year bonds which have a
10-year grace period before principal repayments fall due.
During the first six years, Ecuador can choose whether to pay the coupon on
these bonds in full, or pay a lower coupon and capitalise the balance. It
can thus reduce the initial burden of repayments.
Sir David said that the deal was 'sensitive to the needs of Ecuador' but it
was 'vital that a track record of uninterrupted payments is now
established'. Ecuador started failing to meet interest payments in 1987.
Mr Modesto Correa, the Ecuadorean minister of finance, said that the country
was 'now poised to return to the international capital markets, and resume
its place as a member of the international financial community'. He said the
government was committed to a process of economic stabilisation and
structural reform, and the debt burden had been 'a grave obstacle' to
progress.
The package, modelled on similar agreements pioneered by Mr Nicholas Brady,
former US treasury secretary, offered holders of debt principal a choice
between exchanging it for two types of 30-year bonds.
</TEXT>
